=== TASK ===
# Notifications & Email

## Overview
Build a robust Notifications & Email subsystem supporting transactional and marketing emails, in-app notifications, and push notifications to mobile devices. The system should provide templates, preference management, unsubscribe handling, webhook processing with retry strategies, and end-to-end delivery tracking. It will integrate with SendGrid/Mailgun for email, Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM) and Apple Push Notification Service (APNS) for push notifications, and include an in-app notification center with read/unread state. The feature will be integrated into the StudySpark app and align with the existing design system, ensuring accessibility, reliability, and graceful degradation when external services are unavailable.

## Components to Build
- 1) Email Service Layer
  - Integrations: SendGrid and/or Mailgun templates, transactional vs marketing, high-priority vs bulk sends.
  - Features: template rendering, substitutions, tracking, unsubscribe hooks, bounce/complaint handling.
- 2) Push Notification Service
  - Integrations: FCM for Android/iOS, APNS for iOS where appropriate.
  - Features: device registration, message queues, platform-specific payloads, topic-based broadcasting, opt-in/opt-out management.
- 3) In-App Notification Center
  - UI: list view, detail drawer, read/unread state, archiving, snooze, and actions (mark all read, clear).
  - Persistence: per-user notification store with read state and timestamps.
- 4) Notification Preferences & Unsubscribes
  - UI & API: manage marketing vs transactional preferences, per-channel opt-outs, global unsubscribe, and preference synchronization with email and push.
- 5) Webhook Handler & Retry System
  - Webhooks: receive delivery events (delivered, opened, clicked, bounced, failed), update statuses, and trigger retries where appropriate.
  - Retry Policy: exponential backoff, idempotency, dead-letter handling, and alerting on repeated failures.
- 6) Scheduling & Reminders
  - Time-based triggers for reminders, recurring notifications, and follow-ups based on user activity.
- 7) Admin & Analytics
  - Admin pages for templates, campaigns, delivery stats, open/click rates, and per-user notification history.
- 8) Pages & Routing
  - page_p005, page_p012, page_p011: ensure navigation and UI integrate with existing flows, including notification center links and email preferences.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Core UI Elements
  - In-app notification center view: list with search/filter, read/unread indicators, per-item actions, pagination or infinite scroll, and a detail pane.
  - Notification preferences page: granular controls for email types (transactional vs marketing), push channels (FCM/APNS), and unsubscribe settings.
  - Email template editor (admin-facing): rich text/markdown editor with placeholders, preview pane, and test send button.
  - Admin dashboards: charts and tables for delivery stats, open/cillk rates, bounce reasons, and per-campaign analytics.
  - Reservation of existing design system: rounded cards, pastel gradients, pill-shaped buttons, icons, and accessible contrast.
- Data Handling & Safety
  - Use useState<T[]>([]) for array states (e.g., notifications, templates).
  - Always guard array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Fetch calls and data rendering must validate response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Null safety: use ?? [] for Supabase or API results; default to empty arrays where applicable.
- User Interactions
  - Mark as read/unread, bulk actions, retry sending failed notifications.
  - Unsubscribe flows must reflect instantly in UI and be persistent.
  - Real-time or polling updates for new notifications (prefer WebSocket or SSE if available; fallback to polling with reasonable intervals).
- Accessibility & UX
  - Keyboard navigation, screen-reader friendly labels, visible focus states.
  - Consistent, responsive layouts for desktop and mobile; bottom navigation patterns should adapt to the app’s existing style.

### Backend
- API Endpoints
  - Email
    - POST /api/notifications/email/send: send a transactional/marketing email with templateId, to addresses, substitutions, and tracking options.
    - GET /api/notifications/email/templates: list templates; POST /PUT /DELETE for create/update/delete templates.
    - POST /api/notifications/email/webhook-delivery: handle provider delivery events; update status; trigger retries if configured.
  - Push
    - POST /api/notifications/push/send: enqueue push notification with target device tokens, audience, message, and priority.
    - POST /api/notifications/push/register-device: register device token per user with platform (FCM/APNS), push preferences.
    - POST /api/notifications/push/webhook: handle provider feedback and delivery statuses.
  - In-App
    - GET /api/notifications/in-app: fetch list with pagination; POST /in-app/read to mark as read; POST /in-app/clear.
    - POST /api/notifications/in-app/create: create new in-app notification (admin or system triggers).
  - Preferences
    - GET /api/notifications/preferences: fetch user preferences.
    - POST /api/notifications/preferences: update user preferences (channels, types, unsubscribe).
  - Webhooks & Retries
    - POST /api/webhooks/notifications: collect events from email/push providers; store events; trigger retry queue.
    - Background worker (e.g., Node worker, Bull/Queue, or Supabase edge functions) to manage retries with exponential backoff; dead-letter queue on persistent failures.
- Databases & Tables
  - notifications_in_app (id, user_id, title, message, data, read_at, created_at, type)
  - notification_email_templates (id, name, subject, html_body, text_body, placeholders, created_at, updated_at, is_active)
  - notification_email_logs (id, user_id, template_id, status, message_id/provider_id, opened_at, clicked_at, error_details, retries)
  - notification_push_tokens (id, user_id, device_token, platform, registered_at, preferences)
  - notification_preferences (id, user_id, email_marketing, email_transactional, push_enabled, push_platforms, unsubscribe_status, updated_at)
  - notification_delivery_events (id, target_id, target_type, event_type, event_timestamp, metadata)
  - retry_queue (id, payload_type, payload, retry_count, next_attempt, max_attempts, status)
- Data Integrity & Safety
  - Validate all inputs, use proper defaults, and prevent null dereferences.
  - Ensure idempotency for webhook handling (idempotent processing using event ids).
  - Implement proper error handling and circuit breakers for external services.
- Security & Access
  - Ensure APIs enforce authentication (JWT/session) and proper authorization for admin vs user actions.
  - Protect unsubscribe endpoints from mis-use; log and rate-limit webhook endpoints.
- Validation
  - Input validation on all endpoints: required fields, data types, and length constraints.
  - Email addresses validated with robust regex or library utilities.
  - Device tokens validated by platform (FCM/APNS) and token format.
- Observability
  - Logging at key steps; structured logs with correlation IDs.
  - Metrics endpoints for delivery stats, open/click rates, error counts.
  - Tracing IDs across services to debug end-to-end flows.

### Integration
- Message Flow
  - User action triggers: when a user completes action (e.g., new assignment, reminder), system enqueues in-app notification and schedules email/push if configured.
  - Templates: render email with placeholders; ensure consistent rendering for transactional vs marketing messages.
  - Delivery: email provider handles sending; on webhook, update status and optionally retry.
  - Push: push service constructs payload; delivery status reported via webhook, update status and retry on failure.
- Data Sync
  - Preferences are stored per user and used to filter which channels to deliver to for each event.
  - Unsubscribe events propagate to template rendering and avoid sending to opted-out users.
- Admin Flows
  - Admins can create templates, view delivery stats, and trigger test sends.
  - Admin dashboards aggregate across email, push, and in-app channels.

## User Experience Flow
1. User signs in to StudySpark; navigates to the Notifications & Email center.
2. User views In-App Notification Center:
   - Sees a list of notifications with read/unread status.
   - Can filter by type (reminders, achievements, updates) and search by keywords.
   - Taps a notification to view details; can mark as read/unread, archive, or dismiss.
3. User manages Preferences:
   - Capacity to opt-in/opt-out of marketing emails, transactional emails, and push notifications.
   - Ability to unsubscribe from all communications with an explicit confirmation step.
4. Admin creates/edits Email Templates:
   - Admin creates transactional and marketing templates with placeholders; previews with sample data.
   - Admin triggers test emails to verify rendering.
5. System Triggers:
   - Events trigger in-app notifications, emails, and push messages per user preferences.
   - Webhooks capture provider events; system retries failed deliveries automatically with backoff.
6. Admin Analytics:
   - Admins view dashboards showing delivery rates, opens/clicks, bounce reasons, and per-campaign performance.
   - Ability to drill into per-user notification history for support or user inquiries.
7. Accessibility & Consistency:
   - All notification UI aligns with the design system; accessible controls, readable typography, and color-coded statuses.

